rmes IVA====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro Club Cadet]]\n*[[Blackburn B-2]]\n*[[Blackburn Segrave]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Engines on display==\n[[File:Cirrus Hermes.jpg|right|thumb|A Cirrus Hermes]]\n*A preserved ADC Cirrus II is on display at the [[Science Museum (London)]].\n*A Cirrus Hermes is on display at the [[EAA AirVenture Museum]] in [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]].\n\n==Specifications (Cirrus I)==\n[[File:CirrusIII.JPG|thumb|right|Cirrus III fitted to a [[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]]]]\n{{pistonspecs\n|<!-- If you do not understand how to use this template, please ask at [[Wikipedia talk:WikiProject Aircraft]] -->\n<!-- Please include units where appropriate (main comes first, alt in parentheses). If data are missing, leave the parameter blank (do not delete it). For additional lines, end your alt units with </li> and start a new, fully formatted line with <li> -->\n|ref= ''Lumsden''.<ref name=\"Lumsden\"/>\n|type=Inline, air-cooled, upright 4-cylinder piston engine \n|bore=4.13 in (105&nbsp;mm)\n|stroke=5.12 in (130&nbsp;mm) \n|displacement=274.36 cu in (4.5 L)\n|length=45.8 in (116.3&nbsp;cm)\n|diameter=\n|width=18.26 in (46.4&nbsp;cm)\n|height=34.3 in (87.1&nbsp;cm)\n|weight= lb ( kg)\n|valvetrain=1 inlet and 1 exhaust valve per cylinder\n|supercharger=\n|turbocharger=\n|fuelsystem=1 [[Claudel-Hobson|Claudel]] carburettor\n|fueltype=70 octane\n|oilsystem=\n|coolingsystem=air\n|power=60&nbsp;hp (45 kW)  \n|specpower=\n|compression=4.7:1\n|fuelcon=\n|specfuelcon=\n|oilcon=\n|power/weight= \n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n<!-- other related articles that have not already linked: -->\n|see also=\n\n<!-- designs which were developed into or from this aircraft: -->\n|related=\n*[[ADC Airdisco]]\n\n<!-- aircraft that are of similar role, era, and capability this design: -->\n|similar aircraft=\n\n<!-- relevant lists that this aircraft appears in: -->\n|lists=\n*[[List of aircraft engines]]\n<!-- For aircraft engine articles.  Engines that are of similar to this design: -->\n|similar engines=\n*[[de Havilland Gipsy]]\n<!-- See [[WP:Air/PC]] for more explanation of these fields. -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* The Aviation Ancestry Database of British Aviation Advertisements 1909-1990. [http://aviationancestry.co.uk/?searchQuery=cirrus&startYear=1925&endYear=1957 Cirrus advertisements] (retrieved 23 April 2020).\n* Gunston, Bill. ''World Encyclopaedia of Aero Engines''. Cambridge, England. Patrick Stephens Limited, 1989. {{ISBN|1-85260-163-9}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Frachet |first=Andr\u00e9 |date=12 June 1930|title=Le monoplan Koolhoven F.K.42 |journal=Les Ailes|issue=469 |pages=3|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6553736r/f3}}\n*{{cite book |title= British Civil Aircraft 1919-72|last=Jackson|first=A.J.| year=1973|volume= 2|publisher=Putnam Publishing |location=London |isbn=0 85177 813 5}}\n* Lumsden, Alec. ''British Piston Engines and their Aircraft''. Marlborough, Wiltshire: Airlife Publishing, 2003. {{ISBN|1-85310-294-6}}.\n* Taylor, Douglas R. ''Boxkite to Jet: The Remarkable Career of Frank B. Halford''. Rolls-Royce Heritage Trust. 1999. {{ISBN|1 872922 16 3}}.\n*{{cite book |title= De Nederlandse vliegtuigen |last=Wesselink|first=Theo|last2= Postma|first2=Thijs|year=1982|publisher=Romem  |location=Haarlem |isbn=90 228 3792 0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cirrus engines}}\n*[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1929/1929%20-%201266.html Period engine advertisement - ''Flight'', June 1929]\n\n{{ADC aeroengines}}\n{{Cirrus aeroengines}}\n\n[[Category:1920s aircraft piston engines]]\n[[Category:ADC aircraft engines|Cirrus]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n |name = Cirrus \n |image = ADCCirrusII.JPG\n |caption = ADC Cirrus II at the [[Science Museum (London)|Science Museum, London]]\n}}{{Infobox aircraft engine\n |type=Air-cooled 4-cylinder inline piston engine\n |manufacturer=[[Aircraft Disposal Company]], [[Cirrus Aero-Engines|Cirrus Aero-Engines Limited]], [[Blackburn Aircraft]]\n |national origin=United Kingdom\n |first run={{avyear|1925}}\n |major applications=[[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]] <br>[[Avro Avian]]\n |number built =  \n |program cost = \n |unit cost = \n |developed from = \n |developed into = \n |variants with their own articles =\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''ADC Cirrus''', '''Cirrus Hermes''' and '''Blackburn Cirrus''' are a series of British aero engines originating in the mid-1920s and continuing in production, under various changes of ownership, until the 1950s.\n\nThe Cirrus range were all four-cylinder inline engines, with earlier ones upright and later designs inverted. They were widely used for private and light aircraft.\n\n==Design and development==\nThe Cirrus engine originated in [[Geoffrey de Havilland]]'s quest for a powerplant suited to a light two-seat sports biplane which would become the [[de Havilland Moth]]. The [[Aircraft Disposal Company]], also known as Airdisco and ADC, were producing the low-cost [[ADC Airdisco|Airdisco]] V8 which had been developed by [[Frank Halford]] from their large stocks of war surplus [[Renault]] V8 aero engines. De Havilland realised that half of this engine would make an air-cooled four-cylinder inline engine of just the right size and at very low cost. He persuaded Halford to undertake its design and development. It became the first Cirrus engine.<ref name=\"Taylor>Taylor 1999</ref>\n\nThe original '''ADC Cirrus''' engines were all designed by Halford and built by ADC. The 90&nbsp;hp (67&nbsp;kW) Cirrus I, passed its 50-hour [[Type certificate|type rating]] in 1925. De Havilland launched his product as the [[de Havilland Cirrus Moth|Cirrus Moth]] and it proved a winning formula. The engine was soon adopted for other aircraft. Later versions named the Cirrus II, and Cirrus III were produced each with slightly greater displacement and power (Cirrus II - 85&nbsp;hp, Cirrus III - 90&nbsp;hp).<ref name=\"Taylor>Taylor 1999</ref><ref name=\"gunston\">Gunston 1989</ref>\n\nWhen ADC ran out of the Renault engines, Cirrus Aero Engines Limited was formed in 1927 to manufacture the Cirrus models from scratch.\n\nThe Cirrus III was also produced/converted by American Cirrus Engines Inc., Belleville NJ (later A.C.E. Corp, Marysville MI.).\n\nThe Cirrus company became Cirrus Hermes in 1931 when it was bought by the [[Hermes Engine Company]]. The next model line, Hermes I, II, III and IV were produced ranging in power from 105&nbsp;hp to 140&nbsp;hp depending on type.\n<ref>Lumsden 2003, p.132.</ref>\n\nWhile the Hermes II and III were uprights like their predecessors, the Hermes II B introduced a major change with the cylinders being inverted for the first time. The resulting high propeller line allowed the top of the engine to be lowered, which significantly improved the pilot's view in a single-engined type. All subsequent models would be inverted.<ref name=\"Taylor>Taylor 1999</ref><ref name=\"gunston\">Gunston 1989</ref>\n\nIn 1934 the company was taken over again by [[Blackburn Aircraft Limited]] and moved to Brough in Yorkshire. The company continued manufacturing selling the engines under its old name. In 1935 it launched the [[Blackburn Cirrus Minor|Cirrus Minor]] and [[Blackburn Cirrus Major|Cirrus Major]].\n\nDuring and after WWII Blackburn produced uprated versions of the Cirrus Minor and Major. In 1948 it introduced the [[Blackburn Cirrus Bombardier]] with fuel injection and a higher compression ratio, giving increased output.<ref name=\"Lumsden\">Lumsden 2003, p. 130.</ref>\n\nWhen Blackburn Aircraft merged with [[General Aircraft Limited]] (GAL) in 1949, becoming Blackburn & General Aircraft Limited, it continued to market the Minor, Major and Bombardier range until the late 1950s.\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:Cirrus engines.jpg|thumb|A comparison of Cirrus Hermes I (left) and Cirrus III (right)]]\n[[File:Cirrus-Hermes I in Roe IV triplane replica.jpg|thumb|Cirrus-Hermes I engine in Roe IV replica, Shuttleworth collection]]\nVariants are listed under the brand which introduced them. Some continued in production under new ownership.\n<!-- The majority of information is taken from the Aviation Ancestry collection of commercial advertisements: http://aviationancestry.co.uk/?searchQuery=cirrus&startYear=1925&endYear=1957 It may not be ideal but it is better than what was here before -->\n===ADC===\n;Cirrus I\n:(1925)\n;Cirrus II\n:(1926)\n;Cirrus III\n:(1929)\n;Cirrus IIIA\n:(1933)\n;Hermes I\n:(1929)\n===American Cirrus Engines Inc===\n;American Cirrus III\n:\n;American Cirrus III Hi-drive\n:\n===Cirrus Hermes===\n;Hermes II\n:(1930).\n;Hermes IIB\n:(1932). First inverted engine\n;Hermes III\n:(1932). Upright\n;Hermes IV\n:(1930) Inverted. The Hermes IV A with opposite-handed rotation was introduced around 1934.\n;[[Blackburn Cirrus Minor|Cirrus Minor]]\n:(1935). Inverted.\n;[[Blackburn Cirrus Major|Cirrus Major]]\n:(1935). Inverted.\n\n===Blackburn===\n;[[Blackburn Cirrus Minor]]\n:(1935) Mk I and II variants.\n;[[Blackburn Cirrus Major]]\n:(1935) Mk I, II and III variants.\n;[[Blackburn Cirrus Midget]]\n:(1938) Prototype. Not manufactured.\n;[[Blackburn Cirrus Bombardier]]\n:(1948). Fuel injection.\n\n==Applications==\n''List from Lumsden''<ref>Lumsden 2003, pp. 130-132.</ref> except where noted. The list includes trial installations where a different make was principally adopted.\n\n===Cirrus===\n====Cirrus I====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro Avian]]\n*[[Avro Baby]]\n*[[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]]\n*[[Short Mussel]]\n*[[Westland Widgeon (fixed wing)|Westland Widgeon]]\n{{div col end}}\n====Cirrus II====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro Avian]]\n*[[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]]\n*[[de Havilland DH.71 Tiger Moth]]\n*[[Piaggio P.9]]\n*[[Short Mussel]]\n*[[Westland Widgeon (fixed wing)|Westland Widgeon]]\n*[[Bloudek XV Lojze]]\n{{div col end}}\n====Cirrus III====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro Avian]]\n*[[Blackburn Bluebird]]\n*[[Cierva C.17]]\n*[[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]]\n*[[de Havilland DH.71 Tiger Moth]]\n*[[Dudley Watt D.W.2]]\n*[[Emsco B-4 Cirrus]]\n*[[Koolhoven FK.41]]<ref>Jackson p.190 1973</ref>\n*[[Klemm L.26]]\n*[[Klemm L.27]]\n*[[Short Mussel]]\n*[[Simmonds Spartan]]\n*[[Spartan Arrow]]\n*[[Westland IV|Westland Wessex]]\n*[[Westland Widgeon (fixed wing)|Westland Widgeon]]\n{{div col end}}\n====Cirrus IIIA====\n*[[Miles M.2 Hawk]]\n\n===Hermes===\n\n====Hermes I====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro Avian]]\n*[[Blackburn Bluebird]]\n*[[de Havilland DH.60 Moth]]\n*[[Desoutter I]]\n*[[Koolhoven FK.41]]<ref>Jackson p.495 1973</ref>\n*[[Koolhoven FK.42]]<ref>Les Ailes 469, p.3 1930</ref>\n*[[Hawker Tomtit]]\n*[[Hendy 302]]\n*[[Parnall Elf]]\n*[[Saro Cutty Sark]]\n*[[Simmonds Spartan]]\n*[[Southern Martlet]]\n*[[Westland IV|Westland Wessex]]\n*[[Westland Widgeon (fixed wing)|Westland Widgeon]]\n{{div col end}}\n====Hermes II====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro Avian]]\n*[[Blackburn Bluebird]]\n*[[Desoutter I]]\n*[[Spartan Arrow]]\n*[[Spartan Three-Seater]]\n*[[Westland Widgeon (fixed wing)|Westland Widgeon]]\n{{div col end}}\n====Hermes IIB====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Arrow Active]]\n*[[BFW M.23]]\n*[[Klemm L.27]]\n*[[Koolhoven F.K.44]]<ref>Wesselink 1982 p.80</ref>\n*[[Koolhoven F.K.45]]<ref>Wesselink 1982 p.81</ref>\n*[[Spartan Three-Seater]]\n{{div col end}}\n====Hermes IV====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro 643 Cadet]]\n*[[Hendy 302]]\n*[[Miles M.2 Hawk]]\n*[[Percival Gull]]\n*[[Roe IV Triplane replica]]\n*[[Spartan Cruiser]]\n*[[Spartan Three-Seater]]\n{{div col end}}\n====Hermes IVA====\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Avro Club Cadet]]\n*[[Blackburn B-2]]\n*[[Blackburn Segrave]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Engines on display==\n[[File:Cirrus Hermes.jpg|right|thumb|A Cirrus Hermes]]\n*A preserved ADC Cirrus II is on display at the [[Science Museum (London)]].\n*A Cirrus Hermes is on display at the [[EAA Air